result.execSummary:
The defendant Jonathon W Buehl was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] cases #16CF61 and #16CF122 called at 10:35am.
Defendant Jonathon W Buehl in court with Attorney Sylvie H Dahnert.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Service of the Amended Information in Case #16CF61 admitted; reading is waived.
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; pleas of " No Contest " entered on Case #16CF61-Count #1 of the Amended Information, and on Case #16CF122-Count #1; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the pleas, finds Mr. Buehl guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Case #16CF61-Count #2.

On Case #16CF61-Count #1 and on Case #16CF122-Count #1 the Court withholds sentence, and places Mr. Buehl on Probation for two years, with conditions:
--In Case #16CF122 only:  to serve 30 days in the Jefferson County Jail, with work-release privileges, to commence on 9/3/16 at  6:00pm.
---Mr. Buehl is required to report for commencement and service of jail term with absolute sobriety and without non-prescribed controlled substances in his system; non-compliance will result in loss of work-release privileges without further process.
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, and counseling as required by the Agent
--to be subject to random drug and/or alcohol screening
--no possession or consumption of illegal drugs
--to take all prescription medications as prescribed
--no possession or consumption of alcohol
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--no contact with any known drug offender except for treatment purposes as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to maintain employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--to comply with DNA sample provision
--to pay mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges including DNA surcharges
--in Case #16CF122:  to reimburse the drug buy money of $40
--in Case #16CF122: to pay $25 in drug testing fees
--to pay #16CF61: to pay $250 in drug testing fees, joint & several

Days credit for time already served in each case:  30 days 
As to case #16CF122 only:  The Court grants expungement, under Statute 973.015 if Mr. Buehl successfully completes the Probation term. The Court directs Mr. Buehl to contact the Clerk of Courts Office after he has completed the Probation term to inquire about any need for filing a petition for this.
Felony firearm/voting prohibition warnings are given.  
The posted $500 Cash Bail is to be applied toward payment of court financial obligations.
The Court denies the request of Attorney Dahnert to take action on the $750 forfeiture/judgment related to the previous Signature Bond that was found to be in default and forfeited.
recess 11:01am
